[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 13.3: ICD/CPT Hierarchy Navigation
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Simple-Medium · **Phase:** Foundation · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.01 per query
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m A coder is staring at a clinical note that says "patient presents with chest pain, ruled out MI, final diagnosis: costochondritis." They need to assign the right ICD-10 code. They know it's somewhere under musculoskeletal, probably in the M94 range, but is it M94.0? M94.1? And wait, is costochondritis actually Tietze syndrome or is that different? They open the ICD-10 lookup tool, type "costochondritis," get three results, and now they need to understand how those codes relate to each other in the hierarchy. Is one more specific than another? Does the parent code capture the same concept at a less granular level?
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m This is the daily reality of medical coding. ICD-10-CM alone has over 72,000 codes organized in a strict hierarchy: chapters, blocks, categories, subcategories. CPT has over 10,000 procedure codes with their own hierarchical structure. And the two systems cross-reference each other constantly: a diagnosis code justifies a procedure code, and payers maintain complex rules about which combinations are valid.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m The problem gets worse when you zoom out from individual coding to analytics. A population health team wants to know "how many patients have any form of diabetes?" That's not one code. That's an entire subtree: E08 through E13, each with dozens of children. Querying a flat code table means knowing every leaf code in advance. Miss one and your cohort is wrong.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m Then there's the version problem. ICD-10 updates annually. CMS publishes new codes, retires old ones, and reclassifies existing ones every October 1st. CPT updates quarterly. Your system needs to answer questions like "what was the parent of this code in FY2024?" and "which codes were added under this category in the latest release?" A flat lookup table can't do this without rebuilding the entire thing every cycle.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m Knowledge graphs solve this by representing codes as nodes and their relationships (parent-child, cross-walks, supersedes, groups-with) as edges. Instead of searching a flat list, you traverse a hierarchy. Instead of maintaining cross-reference tables, you query relationship paths. Instead of rebuilding for version changes, you add new nodes and edges while preserving history.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Hierarchical Code Systems as Graphs
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ### Why Medical Code Systems Are Naturally Graphs
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ICD-10-CM has a tree structure baked into its design. The code itself encodes the hierarchy:
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m E11       → Type 2 diabetes mellitus (category)
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m E11.6     → Type 2 diabetes with complications (subcategory)
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m E11.65    → Type 2 diabetes with hyperglycemia (further specificity)
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m E11.65x1  → ... with subsequent encounter (extension)
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m Each level adds specificity. The parent-child relationship is implicit in the code structure. But here's what makes it interesting: the relationships between codes go far beyond simple parent-child. ICD-10 codes have "excludes1" relationships (mutually exclusive, never code together), "excludes2" relationships (not included here, but can be coded together if documented), "includes" notes, and "code first" / "use additional code" instructions that create directed edges between codes in completely different chapters.
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m CPT has its own hierarchy: sections (Surgery, Radiology, Medicine), subsections, headings, and individual codes. But CPT also has modifier relationships, add-on code dependencies (codes that can only be reported with a primary code), and bundling rules (multiple codes that collapse into one for billing purposes).
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m The cross-walk between ICD and CPT is where it gets genuinely complex. A procedure code is only payable when paired with a diagnosis code that justifies medical necessity. These pairings aren't one-to-one. A single CPT code might be justified by dozens of ICD codes. A single ICD code might justify dozens of procedures. And payers maintain their own proprietary variations on these rules.
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m This is a graph problem. Nodes are codes. Edges are typed relationships: `IS_CHILD_OF`, `EXCLUDES`, `CROSS_WALKS_TO`, `BUNDLES_WITH`, `REQUIRES_MODIFIER`, `SUPERSEDED_BY`. Once you model it this way, questions that were painful SQL queries become simple graph traversals.
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m ### Graph Databases vs. Relational Approaches
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m You can model hierarchies in a relational database. People do it all the time with adjacency lists, nested sets, or materialized path columns. For simple parent-child lookups, this works fine. But the moment you need multi-hop traversals ("find all codes within 3 levels of this code that cross-walk to any CPT code in the 99200 range"), relational queries become recursive CTEs that are hard to write, hard to optimize, and hard to maintain.
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m Graph databases store relationships as first-class citizens. A traversal query like "start at E11, walk all children to depth 4, filter by those with a CROSS_WALKS_TO edge to any node in the CPT Surgery section" is a natural expression in a graph query language. The database engine optimizes for exactly this access pattern.
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m The main graph database paradigms:
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m **Property graphs** (Neo4j, Amazon Neptune, TinkerPop-compatible systems): Nodes and edges both carry properties (key-value pairs). Edges are typed and directed. Query languages include Cypher (Neo4j), Gremlin (TinkerPop), and openCypher. This is the most common model for healthcare ontology work because the property bags on edges let you attach metadata like "effective date," "source authority," and "confidence level."
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m **RDF triple stores** (Amazon Neptune in RDF mode, Blazegraph, Stardog): Everything is a subject-predicate-object triple. Query language is SPARQL. This model aligns naturally with formal ontologies (SNOMED-CT is distributed as RDF). If you're integrating with existing biomedical ontologies, RDF might be the path of least resistance. The tradeoff is that SPARQL is more verbose than Cypher for simple traversals.
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m **Hybrid approaches**: Some teams use a relational database for the flat code lookups (fast, simple, well-understood) and a graph database for the relationship queries (traversals, path-finding, cross-walks). This avoids forcing simple lookups through a graph engine while still getting graph benefits for complex queries.
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m ### The Version Problem
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m Medical code systems change. ICD-10-CM updates annually (effective October 1). CPT updates annually with quarterly corrections. When a code is retired, you can't just delete it. Historical claims reference it. Analytics over time periods spanning a version boundary need to understand that code X in 2023 became code Y in 2024.
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m In a graph model, versioning becomes edge metadata. A `SUPERSEDED_BY` edge connects the old code to the new one, with an effective date. A `VALID_IN` edge connects a code to a fiscal year node. Queries can be scoped to a specific version ("show me the E11 subtree as of FY2024") or span versions ("show me all codes that have ever mapped to this concept").
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m This is dramatically cleaner than the relational alternative, which typically involves either maintaining separate tables per version (explosion of tables) or adding valid_from/valid_to columns to every row (complex WHERE clauses on every query).
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m ### Traversal Patterns That Matter
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m The queries you'll actually run against a medical code hierarchy graph fall into a few categories:
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m **Ancestor/descendant queries.** "Give me all codes under E11" (for cohort building). "What's the chapter-level parent of M94.0?" (for reporting rollups). These are depth-first or breadth-first traversals along `IS_CHILD_OF` edges.
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m **Sibling queries.** "What other codes share the same parent as this one?" Useful for suggesting alternative codes during coding. "You picked E11.65, but did you consider E11.64 or E11.69?"
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m **Cross-walk queries.** "Which CPT codes are justified by this ICD code?" or "Which diagnoses support medical necessity for this procedure?" These traverse `CROSS_WALKS_TO` edges, potentially filtered by payer-specific rules.
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m **Exclusion queries.** "Can I code E11.65 and E13.65 on the same claim?" Check for `EXCLUDES1` edges between the two codes or their ancestors.
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m **Path queries.** "What's the shortest path between these two codes in the hierarchy?" Useful for measuring semantic distance between diagnoses.
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m **Temporal queries.** "What changed in the E11 subtree between FY2024 and FY2025?" Compare edges with different version metadata.
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m ### General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m [Code Source Files] → [Parser/Loader] → [Graph Database] → [Query API] → [Consumers]
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m      (CMS, AMA)         (ETL)            (Nodes + Edges)    (REST/GraphQL)   (Coding tools,
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m                                                                                Analytics,
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m                                                                                Rules engines)
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m **Source ingestion.** CMS publishes ICD-10-CM as downloadable flat files (tabular format with parent-child relationships encoded positionally). AMA publishes CPT in various formats. Cross-walk files come from CMS (Medicare) and individual payers. Your ETL pipeline parses these into nodes and edges.
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m **Graph storage.** Codes become nodes with properties (description, effective date, status). Relationships become typed edges with properties (relationship type, source authority, version). The graph accumulates over time rather than being rebuilt.
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m **Query layer.** A service exposes traversal operations as API endpoints. Consumers don't write raw graph queries; they call endpoints like `/codes/{code}/ancestors`, `/codes/{code}/crosswalks?target_system=CPT`, `/codes/{code}/children?depth=3`.
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m **Consumers.** Coding assistance tools, analytics platforms, rules engines, and reporting systems all query the same graph through the API. Each gets the traversal depth and relationship types relevant to their use case.
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 103     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Amazon Neptune for graph storage and traversal.** Neptune is AWS's managed graph database, supporting both property graph (Gremlin/openCypher) and RDF (SPARQL) query models. For ICD/CPT hierarchy navigation, the property graph model with openCypher is the natural fit: codes are nodes with properties, relationships are typed edges with metadata. Neptune handles the index management, replication, and backup that you'd otherwise manage yourself. It's also on the HIPAA eligible services list, which matters because code assignments on claims are PHI-adjacent (they're part of the designated record set).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Neptune for graph storage and traversal.** Neptune is AWS's managed graph database, supporting both property graph (Gremlin/openCypher) and RDF (SPARQL) query models. For ICD/CPT hierarchy navigation, the property graph model with openCypher is the natural fit: codes are nodes with properties, relationships are typed edges with metadata. Neptune handles the index management, replication, and backup that you'd otherwise manage yourself. It's also on the HIPAA eligible services list, which matters because code assignments on claims are PHI-adjacent (they're part of the designated record set). Use Neptune's reader endpoint for query traffic and the cluster (writer) endpoint for bulk loads so read and write workloads don't compete.
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for source file staging.** CMS and AMA publish code files as downloadable archives. These land in S3 as the first step of the ingestion pipeline. S3 also serves as the staging area for Neptune bulk load operations, which expect source data in S3.
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Lambda for ETL orchestration.** The parsing and loading pipeline runs periodically (annually for ICD, quarterly for CPT) and is a short-lived batch job. Lambda functions parse the source files, transform them into Neptune bulk load format (CSV with node/edge headers), and trigger the load. For the annual ICD update, this is a few minutes of compute.
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon API Gateway + Lambda for the query API.** Downstream consumers need a REST interface, not direct graph database access. API Gateway provides the HTTP layer; Lambda functions translate REST requests into openCypher queries, execute them against Neptune, and return structured JSON. This also gives you throttling, authentication, and usage tracking for free.
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon ElastiCache (Redis) for query caching.** Hierarchy traversals are deterministic for a given code version. The children of E11 don't change between October updates. Caching traversal results in Redis eliminates repeated graph queries for popular codes and keeps response times under 50ms for cached paths.
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m     A[CMS/AMA Code Files] -->|Download| B[S3 Bucket\ncode-sources/]
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m     B -->|Parse & Transform| C[Lambda\ncode-etl]
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Bulk Load CSV| D[S3 Bucket\nneptune-staging/]
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m     D -->|Neptune Bulk Loader| E[Amazon Neptune\nCode Graph]
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m     F[API Gateway\n/codes/*] -->|REST| G[Lambda\nquery-handler]
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|Check Cache| H[ElastiCache Redis]
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m     H -->|Cache Miss| G
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|openCypher| E
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|JSON Response| F
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m     F --> I[Coding Tools]
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m     F --> J[Analytics Platform]
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m     F --> K[Rules Engine]
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m     style E fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m     style H fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 140     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Neptune, Amazon S3, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon ElastiCache (Redis) |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 141     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `neptune-db:*` (scoped to cluster), `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `elasticache:*` (scoped to cluster), `lambda:InvokeFunction` |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 142     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed. Code assignments linked to patients are part of the designated record set. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Neptune, Amazon S3, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon ElastiCache (Redis), AWS KMS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Query handler Lambda: `neptune-db:ReadDataViaQuery`, `neptune-db:GetQueryStatus` (scoped to cluster ARN). ETL Lambda: `neptune-db:WriteDataViaQuery`, `neptune-db:ReadDataViaQuery`, `neptune-db:GetLoaderStatus` (scoped to cluster ARN). Both: `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject` (scoped to relevant buckets), `kms:Decrypt`, `kms:GenerateDataKey` (scoped to S3 encryption key). |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | BAA must be signed. Code assignments linked to patients are PHI (part of the designated record set). |
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | Neptune: encryption at rest (enabled at cluster creation, cannot be added later). S3: SSE-KMS. ElastiCache: in-transit and at-rest encryption. All API calls over TLS. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 144     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | Neptune requires VPC deployment. Lambda functions must be in the same VPC with appropriate security groups. VPC endpoints for S3 and CloudWatch Logs. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 145     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for Neptune API calls and S3 access logging. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Neptune requires VPC deployment. Lambda functions in same VPC with security groups: Lambda SG allows outbound to Neptune (port 8182), ElastiCache (port 6379), and VPC endpoints (port 443). Neptune SG allows inbound from Lambda SG on 8182. ElastiCache SG allows inbound from Lambda SG on 6379. VPC endpoints required: S3 (gateway), CloudWatch Logs (interface), KMS (interface). If Lambdas have no NAT/internet egress, also add Neptune management endpoint. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled for Neptune API calls and S3 access logging. Enable Neptune audit logging via cluster parameter group (`neptune_enable_audit_log = 1`) for query-level audit trail. |
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | CMS publishes ICD-10-CM files at [cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes](https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes). CPT requires AMA license. Use ICD-10-CM (free) for development; add CPT when licensed. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 147     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Neptune db.r5.large: ~$0.348/hr (~$254/month). ElastiCache cache.t3.medium: ~$0.068/hr (~$50/month). Lambda and API Gateway negligible at query volumes under 1M/month. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Neptune db.r5.large: ~$0.348/hr (~$254/month). Neptune I/O: ~$0.20 per million requests (at 1M queries/month with 85% cache hit rate, expect ~150K Neptune I/Os, negligible; spikes during cache-cold periods post-update). ElastiCache cache.t3.medium: ~$0.068/hr (~$50/month). Lambda and API Gateway negligible at query volumes under 1M/month. |
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 153     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon Neptune** | Stores code hierarchy as property graph; executes traversal queries |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Neptune** | Stores code hierarchy as property graph; executes traversal queries (reader endpoint for queries, cluster endpoint for loads) |
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stages source code files and Neptune bulk load CSVs |
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | ETL pipeline (parse/transform/load) and query handler |
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | REST interface for downstream consumers |
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon ElastiCache** | Caches traversal results for sub-50ms response on popular codes |
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption keys for Neptune, S3, and ElastiCache |
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Query latency metrics, cache hit rates, ETL job monitoring |
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Parse ICD-10-CM source files into graph nodes and edges.** CMS distributes ICD-10-CM as a set of flat files: a tabular code list with descriptions, and an "order file" that encodes the hierarchy through indentation levels and parent references. This step reads those files and produces two outputs: a node list (one row per code with its properties) and an edge list (one row per relationship). The hierarchy is encoded in the code structure itself (E11 is parent of E11.6, which is parent of E11.65), but the source files also contain explicit "includes," "excludes1," and "excludes2" annotations that become additional edge types. Skip this step and you have no graph to query. Get the parsing wrong and your hierarchy traversals return incorrect results, which means wrong cohort counts and invalid coding suggestions.
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION parse_icd10_to_graph(source_file_path):
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m     // Read the CMS order file. Each line contains:
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Code (positional, chars 1-7)
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Whether it's a "header" (non-billable parent) or "billable" leaf
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m     //   - Short description and long description
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m     raw_codes = read and parse CMS order file from source_file_path
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m     nodes = empty list   // will hold one entry per code
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m     edges = empty list   // will hold one entry per relationship
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each code_entry in raw_codes:
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m         // Create a node for this code
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m         node = {
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m             id:          code_entry.code,                    // e.g., "E11.65"
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m             label:       "ICD10CM",                          // node type label
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m             description: code_entry.long_description,        // human-readable name
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m             short_desc:  code_entry.short_description,       // abbreviated name
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m             is_billable: code_entry.is_billable,             // true = leaf code, false = category header
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m             chapter:     derive_chapter(code_entry.code),    // e.g., "4" for E codes (Endocrine)
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m             version:     "FY2026"                            // fiscal year this code is valid in
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m         append node to nodes
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m         // Derive parent from code structure:
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m         //   E11.65 → parent is E11.6
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m         //   E11.6  → parent is E11
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m         //   E11    → parent is E08-E13 block (or chapter node)
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m         parent_code = derive_parent(code_entry.code)
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m         IF parent_code is not null:
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m             edge = {
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m                 source: code_entry.code,
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m                 target: parent_code,
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m                 type:   "IS_CHILD_OF"
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m             append edge to edges
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse the excludes/includes annotations (separate CMS file)
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m     annotations = parse_annotation_file(source_file_path + "/annotations")
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each annotation in annotations:
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m         edge = {
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m             source:     annotation.code,
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m             target:     annotation.referenced_code,
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m             type:       annotation.relationship_type,   // "EXCLUDES1", "EXCLUDES2", "CODE_FIRST", etc.
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m             note:       annotation.description          // human-readable explanation
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m         append edge to edges
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN nodes, edges
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Parse CPT codes and cross-walk mappings.** CPT has its own hierarchy (sections, subsections, code ranges) and the critical cross-walk file maps ICD-10 diagnosis codes to CPT procedure codes for medical necessity validation. The cross-walk data comes from CMS for Medicare (the "Medically Unlikely Edits" and "Correct Coding Initiative" files) and from individual payers for commercial plans. This step produces additional nodes (CPT codes) and cross-walk edges connecting the two systems. Without this step, your graph answers hierarchy questions but can't answer the cross-system questions that coding and billing teams actually need.
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION parse_cpt_and_crosswalks(cpt_source, crosswalk_source):
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m     nodes = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m     edges = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse CPT hierarchy (requires AMA license)
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m     cpt_codes = parse_cpt_file(cpt_source)
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cpt_entry in cpt_codes:
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m         node = {
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m             id:          "CPT:" + cpt_entry.code,        // prefix to distinguish from ICD
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m             label:       "CPT",
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m             description: cpt_entry.description,
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m             section:     cpt_entry.section,              // e.g., "Surgery", "Medicine"
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m             subsection:  cpt_entry.subsection,
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m             is_addon:    cpt_entry.is_addon_code,        // add-on codes can't be billed alone
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m             version:     "2026"
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m         append node to nodes
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m         // CPT parent-child from section hierarchy
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m         IF cpt_entry.parent_range is not null:
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m             edge = {
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m                 source: "CPT:" + cpt_entry.code,
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m                 target: "CPT:" + cpt_entry.parent_range,
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m                 type:   "IS_CHILD_OF"
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m             append edge to edges
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse ICD-to-CPT cross-walk (medical necessity mappings)
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m     crosswalks = parse_crosswalk_file(crosswalk_source)
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each mapping in crosswalks:
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m         edge = {
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m             source:    mapping.icd_code,                 // ICD-10-CM code
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m             target:    "CPT:" + mapping.cpt_code,        // CPT code
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m             type:      "CROSS_WALKS_TO",
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m             payer:     mapping.payer,                     // "Medicare" or specific payer
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m             effective: mapping.effective_date,
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m             end_date:  mapping.end_date                   // null if currently active
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m         append edge to edges
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN nodes, edges
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 264     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 3: Bulk load into Neptune.** Neptune's bulk loader expects CSV files in S3 with specific header conventions. Node files need `~id`, `~label`, and property columns. Edge files need `~id`, `~from`, `~to`, `~label`, and property columns. This step transforms the parsed data into that format and triggers the load. Bulk loading is dramatically faster than inserting nodes one at a time via Gremlin or openCypher (minutes vs. hours for 70,000+ nodes). The load is idempotent if you use consistent IDs: reloading the same file updates existing nodes rather than creating duplicates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Bulk load into Neptune.** Neptune's bulk loader expects CSV files in S3 with specific header conventions. Node files need `~id`, `~label`, and property columns. Edge files need `~id`, `~from`, `~to`, `~label`, and property columns. This step transforms the parsed data into that format and triggers the load. Bulk loading is dramatically faster than inserting nodes one at a time via Gremlin or openCypher (minutes vs. hours for 70,000+ nodes). For true upsert behavior (updating existing nodes with new property values on reload), use `mode=AUTO` with `updateSingleCardinalityProperties=TRUE`. Without these parameters, reloading a file with changed descriptions will skip existing nodes rather than updating them.
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION load_graph_to_neptune(nodes, edges, neptune_endpoint, s3_staging_bucket):
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m     // Transform nodes into Neptune CSV format
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m     node_csv = format_as_neptune_csv(nodes, type="nodes")
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m     // Columns: ~id, ~label, description:String, is_billable:Bool, chapter:String, version:String
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m     // Transform edges into Neptune CSV format
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m     edge_csv = format_as_neptune_csv(edges, type="edges")
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m     // Columns: ~id, ~from, ~to, ~label, note:String, payer:String, effective:Date
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m     // Upload to S3 staging bucket
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m     upload node_csv to s3_staging_bucket + "/nodes/icd10_nodes.csv"
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m     upload edge_csv to s3_staging_bucket + "/edges/icd10_edges.csv"
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m     // Trigger Neptune bulk load
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m     response = call Neptune Loader API:
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m         source      = s3_staging_bucket
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m         format      = "csv"
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m         iamRoleArn  = neptune_load_role_arn    // Neptune needs an IAM role to read from S3
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m         region      = current_region
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         mode        = "AUTO"                   // upsert: update existing, insert new
[0m[49m[39m  286, 287[0m:[39m[49m         failOnError = "FALSE"                  // log errors but continue loading valid records
[0m[49m[39m  287, 288[0m:[39m[49m         parallelism = "HIGH"                   // use all available loader threads
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         updateSingleCardinalityProperties = "TRUE"  // update properties on existing nodes
[0m[49m[39m  288, 290[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  289, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // Monitor load status
[0m[49m[39m  290, 292[0m:[39m[49m     WHILE load is not complete:
[0m[49m[39m  291, 293[0m:[39m[49m         status = check Neptune Loader status(response.loadId)
[0m[49m[39m  292, 294[0m:[39m[49m         IF status == "LOAD_FAILED":
[0m[49m[39m  293, 295[0m:[39m[49m             log error details
[0m[49m[39m  294, 296[0m:[39m[49m             RAISE exception
[0m[49m[39m  295, 297[0m:[39m[49m         wait 5 seconds
[0m[49m[39m  296, 298[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  297, 299[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN load statistics (nodes loaded, edges loaded, errors)
[0m[49m[39m  298, 300[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  299, 301[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  300, 302[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Query the hierarchy.** This is where the graph pays off. Queries that would be recursive CTEs in SQL become simple traversal expressions in openCypher. The query handler Lambda receives REST requests, translates them into openCypher, executes against Neptune, and returns structured JSON. Common query patterns: get all descendants (for cohort building), get ancestors (for rollup reporting), find cross-walks (for coding validation), check exclusions (for claim editing). Each query type is a different traversal pattern but they all follow the same execute-and-format flow.
[0m[49m[39m  301, 303[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  302, 304[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  303, 305[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION handle_query(request):
[0m[49m[39m  304, 306[0m:[39m[49m     code       = request.path_params.code          // e.g., "E11"
[0m[49m[39m  305, 307[0m:[39m[49m     query_type = request.path_params.query_type    // "children", "ancestors", "crosswalks", "exclusions"
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 306     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     depth      = request.query_params.depth OR 99  // how many levels to traverse (default: all)
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 307     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     version    = request.query_params.version OR "current"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     depth      = request.query_params.depth OR 10  // how many levels to traverse (default: 10)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     version    = request.query_params.version OR current_fiscal_year()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     page_size  = request.query_params.limit OR 100
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     offset     = request.query_params.offset OR 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate input: reject malformed codes at the API layer.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // ICD-10 pattern: letter + digits + optional dot + digits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // CPT pattern: "CPT:" prefix + 4-5 digits
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF code does not match "^[A-Z][0-9]{2}(\.[0-9A-Z]{1,4})?$"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m        AND code does not match "^(CPT:)?[0-9]{4,5}$":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN 400 Bad Request ("Invalid code format")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Clamp depth to prevent unreasonably broad traversals
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     depth = max(1, min(depth, 20))
[0m[49m[39m  308, 322[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 309     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Check cache first (traversals are deterministic per version)
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 310     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     cache_key = build_cache_key(code, query_type, depth, version)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Check cache first.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Key includes resolved version (not "current") to avoid ambiguity across updates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cache_key = build_cache_key(code, query_type, depth, version, page_size, offset)
[0m[49m[39m  311, 326[0m:[39m[49m     cached = lookup cache_key in Redis
[0m[49m[39m  312, 327[0m:[39m[49m     IF cached is not null:
[0m[49m[39m  313, 328[0m:[39m[49m         RETURN cached
[0m[49m[39m  314, 329[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 315     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Build the appropriate openCypher query
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Build the appropriate openCypher query.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Note: Neptune openCypher does not support parameterized variable-length
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // path bounds. The depth value must be interpolated as a literal integer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // (safe here because we validated it as an integer above).
[0m[49m[39m  316, 334[0m:[39m[49m     IF query_type == "children":
[0m[49m[39m  317, 335[0m:[39m[49m         // Find all descendants up to specified depth
[0m[49m[39m  318, 336[0m:[39m[49m         cypher = "
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 319     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m             MATCH path = (start {id: $code})<-[:IS_CHILD_OF*1..$depth]-(descendant)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             MATCH path = (start {id: $code})<-[:IS_CHILD_OF*1..{depth}]-(descendant)
[0m[49m[39m  320, 338[0m:[39m[49m             WHERE descendant.version = $version
[0m[49m[39m  321, 339[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN descendant.id AS code,
[0m[49m[39m  322, 340[0m:[39m[49m                    descendant.description AS description,
[0m[49m[39m  323, 341[0m:[39m[49m                    descendant.is_billable AS billable,
[0m[49m[39m  324, 342[0m:[39m[49m                    length(path) AS depth_level
[0m[49m[39m  325, 343[0m:[39m[49m             ORDER BY descendant.id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             SKIP $offset LIMIT $page_size
[0m[49m[39m  326, 345[0m:[39m[49m         "
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // {depth} is interpolated as a literal integer, not a parameter
[0m[49m[39m  327, 347[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  328, 348[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF query_type == "ancestors":
[0m[49m[39m  329, 349[0m:[39m[49m         // Walk up the hierarchy to the chapter level
[0m[49m[39m  330, 350[0m:[39m[49m         cypher = "
[0m[49m[39m  331, 351[0m:[39m[49m             MATCH path = (start {id: $code})-[:IS_CHILD_OF*1..10]->(ancestor)
[0m[49m[39m  332, 352[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN ancestor.id AS code,
[0m[49m[39m  333, 353[0m:[39m[49m                    ancestor.description AS description,
[0m[49m[39m  334, 354[0m:[39m[49m                    length(path) AS levels_up
[0m[49m[39m  335, 355[0m:[39m[49m             ORDER BY levels_up
[0m[49m[39m  336, 356[0m:[39m[49m         "
[0m[49m[39m  337, 357[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  338, 358[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF query_type == "crosswalks":
[0m[49m[39m  339, 359[0m:[39m[49m         // Find all codes in the other system linked by cross-walk edges
[0m[49m[39m  340, 360[0m:[39m[49m         target_system = request.query_params.target OR "CPT"
[0m[49m[39m  341, 361[0m:[39m[49m         cypher = "
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 342     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m             MATCH (start {id: $code})-[:CROSS_WALKS_TO]->(target)
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 343     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m             WHERE target.label = $target_system
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             MATCH (start {id: $code})-[r:CROSS_WALKS_TO]->(target)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             WHERE target.`~label` = $target_system
[0m[49m[39m  344, 364[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN target.id AS code,
[0m[49m[39m  345, 365[0m:[39m[49m                    target.description AS description,
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 346     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m                    relationship.payer AS payer,
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 347     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m                    relationship.effective AS effective_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                    r.payer AS payer,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                    r.effective AS effective_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             SKIP $offset LIMIT $page_size
[0m[49m[39m  348, 369[0m:[39m[49m         "
[0m[49m[39m  349, 370[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  350, 371[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF query_type == "exclusions":
[0m[49m[39m  351, 372[0m:[39m[49m         // Find codes that cannot be reported together with this one
[0m[49m[39m  352, 373[0m:[39m[49m         cypher = "
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 353     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m             MATCH (start {id: $code})-[:EXCLUDES1]-(excluded)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             MATCH (start {id: $code})-[r:EXCLUDES1]-(excluded)
[0m[49m[39m  354, 375[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN excluded.id AS code,
[0m[49m[39m  355, 376[0m:[39m[49m                    excluded.description AS description,
[0m[49m[39m  356, 377[0m:[39m[49m                    'EXCLUDES1' AS exclusion_type
[0m[49m[39m  357, 378[0m:[39m[49m         "
[0m[49m[39m  358, 379[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 359     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Execute against Neptune
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 360     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     result = execute_cypher(neptune_endpoint, cypher, params={code, depth, version})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Execute against Neptune (use reader endpoint for queries)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = execute_cypher(neptune_reader_endpoint, cypher, params={code, version, offset, page_size})
[0m[49m[39m  361, 382[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 362     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Cache the result (TTL = until next version update, or 24 hours as safety)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Cache the result.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // TTL = 24 hours. After a version update, flush the cache (see Step 5).
[0m[49m[39m  363, 385[0m:[39m[49m     store cache_key -> result in Redis with TTL 86400
[0m[49m[39m  364, 386[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  365, 387[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN format_as_json(result)
[0m[49m[39m  366, 388[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  367, 389[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  368, 390[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Handle version transitions.** When CMS publishes a new ICD-10-CM version each October, the graph needs to incorporate the changes without destroying history. New codes get new nodes. Retired codes get a `SUPERSEDED_BY` edge pointing to their replacement. Modified codes get updated properties with the new version tag. This step runs as part of the annual ETL and ensures that queries scoped to any historical version still return correct results. Skip this and you lose the ability to analyze claims across fiscal year boundaries, which breaks any longitudinal analytics.
[0m[49m[39m  369, 391[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  370, 392[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  371, 393[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION apply_version_update(new_version_nodes, new_version_edges, current_version, new_version):
[0m[49m[39m  372, 394[0m:[39m[49m     // Identify changes: new codes, retired codes, modified descriptions
[0m[49m[39m  373, 395[0m:[39m[49m     current_codes = query Neptune for all nodes where version = current_version
[0m[49m[39m  374, 396[0m:[39m[49m     new_codes     = set of new_version_nodes not in current_codes
[0m[49m[39m  375, 397[0m:[39m[49m     retired_codes = set of current_codes not in new_version_nodes
[0m[49m[39m  376, 398[0m:[39m[49m     modified      = set of codes in both but with changed descriptions
[0m[49m[39m  377, 399[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  378, 400[0m:[39m[49m     // Add new codes as new nodes
[0m[49m[39m  379, 401[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each code in new_codes:
[0m[49m[39m  380, 402[0m:[39m[49m         create node in Neptune with version = new_version
[0m[49m[39m  381, 403[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  382, 404[0m:[39m[49m     // Mark retired codes with SUPERSEDED_BY edges
[0m[49m[39m  383, 405[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each code in retired_codes:
[0m[49m[39m  384, 406[0m:[39m[49m         // CMS publishes a "GEMs" (General Equivalence Mappings) file
[0m[49m[39m  385, 407[0m:[39m[49m         // that maps old codes to their replacements
[0m[49m[39m  386, 408[0m:[39m[49m         replacement = lookup_gem_mapping(code, new_version)
[0m[49m[39m  387, 409[0m:[39m[49m         IF replacement exists:
[0m[49m[39m  388, 410[0m:[39m[49m             create edge: code -[:SUPERSEDED_BY {effective: new_version}]-> replacement
[0m[49m[39m  389, 411[0m:[39m[49m         // Mark the old node as inactive but don't delete it
[0m[49m[39m  390, 412[0m:[39m[49m         update node property: code.status = "RETIRED"
[0m[49m[39m  391, 413[0m:[39m[49m         update node property: code.retired_in = new_version
[0m[49m[39m  392, 414[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  393, 415[0m:[39m[49m     // Update modified descriptions
[0m[49m[39m  394, 416[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each code in modified:
[0m[49m[39m  395, 417[0m:[39m[49m         // Don't overwrite: create a versioned property
[0m[49m[39m  396, 418[0m:[39m[49m         update node: code.description = new_description
[0m[49m[39m  397, 419[0m:[39m[49m         update node: code.version = new_version
[0m[49m[39m  398, 420[0m:[39m[49m         // Preserve old description as historical property
[0m[49m[39m  399, 421[0m:[39m[49m         add property: code.description_prior = old_description
[0m[49m[39m  400, 422[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  401, 423[0m:[39m[49m     // Add new version's edges (new cross-walks, updated exclusions)
[0m[49m[39m  402, 424[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each edge in new_version_edges:
[0m[49m[39m  403, 425[0m:[39m[49m         IF edge does not exist in current graph:
[0m[49m[39m  404, 426[0m:[39m[49m             create edge with effective_date = new_version
[0m[49m[39m  405, 427[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Flush the Redis cache after a successful version update.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // All cached traversal results may now be stale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     flush Redis cache (or at minimum, flush keys matching the updated version)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  406, 432[0m:[39m[49m     log "Version update complete: {new_codes.count} added, {retired_codes.count} retired, {modified.count} modified"
[0m[49m[39m  407, 433[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  408, 434[0m:[39m[49m 
